text.tspan: General Notes
Concept: Battery
The Charge Level Meter
Shows the player their current level of permanent and temporary charge. This
indicates to the player what moves they can perform as well as how close the
player is to winning.
The charge level meter is this game’s equivalent of a “health bar” and “mana bar” combined
together into a single UI-element. It is a critical part of the interface that provides players with
information that is relevant at all stages of the game
Each player should be able to easily recognize the charge level of themselves
and each other player.
Permanent charge and temporary charge serve some overlapping purposes, but
interact differently in many ways. Thus, they must be visually distinct.
Frame is shaped like a battery. This helps the player quickly understand that the inside
represents electric energy, while also incentivizing the player to fill the battery up.
The player can gain a maximum of three permanent and temporary charges.
Inner bars represent the level of charge the player is currently at. These bars have three possible
states shown below:
Perma-charge
is a solid, flat color that matches the player’s accent colour.
Temp-charge
matches the player colour like perma-charge. However, it flashes white. This gives it
a more ephemeral appearance to the player, showing that it isn’t “locked in” yet.
Uncharged
is represented by a grey rectangle. This makes it appear more inert and powerless. The
colour of the grey needs to clearly contrast with the vivid charged elements for clarity.
Charge bar is relatively thin so as to not clutter up the player’s view. However, it needs to be tall
enough so that even at a distance you can tell what’s going on.
